{
  "answer": "In Allama Iqbal's poem *Mauj_e_Darya* (\"The Wave\") from *Bang-E-Dara Part 1*, the wave personifies its own restlessness as an essential, sacred torment—an \"unquiet heart\" that keeps it in \"constant torment\" and a \"sacred agony, like quicksilver,\" which is its very element.[^1] This inner agitation drives dynamic actions: leaping toward the moon's pull, writhing and dashing its head against the shore, fleeing the river's \"narrow straits,\" and yearning in anguish for reunion with the ocean's \"vast expanse,\" as a traveler in love with its ultimate goal.[^2]\n\n[^1]: Allama Iqbal, *Bang-E-Dara Part 1*, [p-475086](/works/allama-iqbal-bang-e-dara-part-1-55b25c/31-mauj-e-darya/translation/#p-475086).\n\n[^2]: Allama Iqbal, *Bang-E-Dara Part 1*, [chapter](/works/allama-iqbal-bang-e-dara-part-1-55b25c/31-mauj-e-darya/translation/).",
